as -- t9. Economic Development and Demotic Religiosity / rLandes, Richard -- t10. Back- Biting and Self- Promotion: Th e Work of Merchants of the Cairo Geniza / rGoldberg, Jessica -- t11. John of Salisbury and the Civic Utility of Religion / rSilk, Mark -- tPart III. Cognition, composition, and contagion -- t12. Understanding Contagion: Th e Contaminating Effect of Another's Sin / rKramer, Susan R. -- t13. Calvin's Smile / rMartin, John Jeffries -- t14. Why All the Fuss About the Mind? A Medievalist's Perspective on Cognitive Theory / rClark, Anne L. -- t15. Aspects of Blood Piety in a Late- Medieval English Manuscript: London, British Library MS Additional 37049 / rHennessy, Marlene Villalobos -- t16. Machiavelli, Trauma, and the Scandal of Th e Prince: An Essay in Speculative History / rFrazier, Alison K. -- tPart 4. The matter of person -- t17. Low Country Ascetics and Oriental Luxury: Jacques de Vitry, Marie of Oignies, and the Treasures of Oignies / rFarmer, Sharon -- t18. Crystalline Wombs and Pregnant Hearts: Th e Exuberant Bodies of the Katharinenthal Visitation Group / rJung, Jacqueline E. -- t19. Gluttony and the Anthropology of Pain in Dante's Inferno and Purgatorio / rGragnolati, Manuele -- t20. "Human Heaven": John of Rupescissa's Alchemy at the End of the World / rVun, Leah De -- t21. Magic, Bodies, University Masters, and the Invention of the Late Medieval Witch / rMarrone, Steven P. -- tAfterword: History in the Comic Mode / rFulton, Rachel / Holsinger, Bruce -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this groundbreaking collection, twenty-one prominent medievalists discuss continuity and change in ideas of personhood and community and argue for the viability of the comic mode in the study and recovery of history. These scholars approach their sources not from a particular ideological viewpoint but with an understanding that all topics, questions, and explanations are viable. They draw on a variety of sources in Latin, Arabic, French, German, Middle English, and more, and employ a range of theories and methodologies, always keeping in mind that environments are inseparable from the making of the people who inhabit them and that these people are in part constituted by and understood in terms of their communities. Essays feature close readings of both familiar and lesser known materials, offering provocative interpretations of John of Rupescissa's alchemy; the relationship between the living and the saintly dead in Bernard of Clairvaux's sermons; the nomenclature of heresy in the early eleventh century; the apocalyptic visions of Robert of Uzès; Machiavelli's De principatibus; the role of "demotic religiosity" in economic development; and the visions of Elizabeth of Schönau. Contributors write as historians of religion, art, literature, culture, and society, approaching their subjects through the particular and the singular rather than through the thematic and the theoretical. Playing with the wild possibilities of the historical fragments at their disposal, the scholars in this collection advance a new and exciting approach to writing medieval history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aCivilization, Medieval. 0aCommunity lifezEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aHuman bodyxSocial aspectszEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aIdentity (Psychology)zEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aIndividualityzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMiddle Ages. 0aReligion and sociologyzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSoulxSocial aspectszEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Rachel Fulton, eeditor.1 aHolsinger, Bruce, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is pa